{"name":"Watched","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"Whether your character knows it or not, she’s constantly monitored. This could be because she’s a famous pop star, or a corporate slug just high enough on the ladder to warrant observation. Maybe you’re a mole (or a rat) and the police are constantly feeding your sensory input to the law dog’s data pool. Whatever the reason, your character’s TAP contains software that can be monitored at any time by your overseer.</p><p>While monitoring may not be constant, you should assume that every move you make is logged and filed away “just in case.” Anything that upsets your monitor may warrant a house call. This software can be removed with a successful Hacking attempt but would have immediate repercussions. Work with your GM on the details. </p><p>Note: This Hindrance cannot be taken if you have taken the Unplugged Hindrance.","notes":"Interface Zero 3.0 Players Guide page 42","additionalStats":{},"major":false},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.interface-zero-30.WMumQQ4gv94TyXrX"},"cf":{"id":"temp_1gc4buwp27h","path":"Interface Zero 3.0","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"E4gBZO1FtzzhLOaV"}
{"name":"Trouble Magnet","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"As a Minor Hindrance, the hero stumbles into some sort of trouble at least once per session. Maybe someone recognizes him while he’s trying to infiltrate an EXFOR base, his Stallion runs out of fuel or won’t start, or an angry ex winds up being the one person the party needs information from.</p><p>As a Major Hindrance, anytime the GM must choose a “random character” to be hit, attacked, or otherwise negatively affected by something, it’s this poor schmuck.","notes":"Deadlands Lost Colony page 35","additionalStats":{},"major":true},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.deadlands-lost-colony.qJXDmT2D53Kt6EtU"},"cf":{"id":"temp_3ki8vx1qg59","path":"Deadlands: Lost Colony","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"ENABS65Q9Uighb8h"}
{"name":"Lyin’ Eyes","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"Lies just don’t come easy to this hombre. That sounds all good and noble, but often causes problems when dealing with more nefarious types. A hero with this Hindrance suffers a −2 penalty to all Intimidation and Persuasion rolls where lies—even little ones—must be told. This includes Gambling if the game features any element of bluffing.","notes":"Deadlands Lost Colony page 35","additionalStats":{},"major":false},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.deadlands-lost-colony.M36Fd6bqypAGLBOM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_3ki8vx1qg59","path":"Deadlands: Lost Colony","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"HNTPK6EzUOJtNRL6"}
{"name":"Hyperspace Sickness","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"Something about the character doesn’t sit right with the bizarre warping effects of hyperspace. After each use of Hyperdrive travel, he suffers a level of fatigue that takes 24 hours to fade. Hyperspace Sickness can cause Incapacitation but not death.","notes":"Savage Star Wars page 6","additionalStats":{},"major":false},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.savage-star-wars.ozGGeQJ9L6pumhGM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_ce6vltnlzek","path":"Savage Star Wars","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"Iu1VIkYpp8IjDNKN"}
{"name":"Rebellious","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"Like a lot of colonists who moved to Banshee, you don’t handle authority figures well. Maybe you shoot your mouth off at everyone wearing a badge or ID tag. Maybe you do the exact and orneriest opposite of what you’re told when you don’t like the tone in someone’s voice. Whatever your behavior, you constantly cause trouble with anyone who has the slightest bit of power over you—or thinks they do.","notes":"Deadlands Lost Colony page 35","additionalStats":{},"major":false},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.deadlands-lost-colony.M8xPyuQ0vvO2oDNa"},"cf":{"id":"temp_3ki8vx1qg59","path":"Deadlands: Lost Colony","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"KKY4tac26uYt11qg"}
{"name":"Zero-G Sickness","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"The lack of gravity makes your hero upchuck. He becomes nauseous and might even throw up his dehydrated vittles now and then.</p><p>Those with this affliction are automatically Fatigued in zero-g, which can cause Incapacitation but not death (although he might wish for it). Fatigue is recovered after one hour in any other type of gravity.","notes":"Deadlands Lost Colony page 35","additionalStats":{},"major":false},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.deadlands-lost-colony.5pnNHfN1HLN84Wzl"},"cf":{"id":"temp_3ki8vx1qg59","path":"Deadlands: Lost Colony","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"KfuqAcDANJ8YQN3V"}
{"name":"Grim Servant O’ Death","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"Only Wild Cards can take this Hindrance, and you shouldn’t do it lightly, amigo. Your hero’s a killer. His family’s probably pushing up daisies, his enemies are worm food, and even a few of his friends have holes in them that are suspiciously the same caliber as his very own shootin’ iron.</p><p>The good news is your hombre adds +1 to every damage roll he ever makes, whether it’s from Fighting, Shooting, magic, or even using Athletics to throw things at people in a most inhospitable manner.</p><p>The downside is your hero winds up in the hoosegow or on the run from his enemies a lot. Worse, anytime his attack roll is a Critical Failure, his attack hits the nearest friendly character in sight with a raise! This happens whether the target’s in the line of fire or not. Maybe his gun hand gets jostled, the bullet richochets, or he catches flying shrapnel from an explosion. Other players’ characters are always first choice, but any friendly soul will do in a pinch.</p><p>Even hand-to-hand attacks hit allies when a Grim Servant o’ Death gets violent. This may require a little imagination, but either the weapon flies out of the hero’s hand and strikes his friend, or the hero moves adjacent to his erstwhile comrade and “accidentally” whacks him. Remember, even if you’re using miniatures combat is more fluid than the table-top depicts.","notes":"Deadlands Lost Colony page 34","additionalStats":{},"major":true},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.deadlands-lost-colony.AAIyWRVk8THBPwyV"},"cf":{"id":"temp_3ki8vx1qg59","path":"Deadlands: Lost Colony","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"PrF7aqbybOJB3SBB"}
{"name":"Zero-G Sickness","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"The lack of gravity makes this spacer hurl. He becomes dizzy and throws up intermittently, causing an automatic level of Fatigue when in zero-g and not restrained in some way. Zero-g Fatigue can cause Incapacitation but not death, and is recovered after one hour in any other type of gravity.","notes":"Science Fiction Companion page 11","additionalStats":{},"major":true},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.science-fiction-companion.vmAdR6fJ8I6yBEoP"},"cf":{"id":"temp_5fatrubp5nm","path":"Science Fiction Companion","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"SKXlmdLUjZkxNJFD"}
{"name":"Magnet","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"Whether it’s her looks, fame, or something else you can’t explain, certain people find your hero very alluring. Sadly, they’re never those she wishes were drawn to her. As a Minor Hindrance, one or two fans show up as an inconvenience or occasional distraction.</p><p>The Major version has swarms of fans who could get her into serious trouble. Imagine trying to do a run while hounded by a half-dozen reporters! Example fans include criminal wannabes hoping to curry her favor, journalists, or reality show producers.","notes":"Interface Zero 3.0 Players Guide page 41","additionalStats":{},"major":true},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.interface-zero-30.nhq2Eqou7xNUIQ2C"},"cf":{"id":"temp_1gc4buwp27h","path":"Interface Zero 3.0","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"V032vi5QkEY3igel"}
{"name":"Low-G Worlder","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"The being hails from a world with light gravity, making his muscles weak compared to most other species.</p><p>He subtracts 1 from all Strength rolls (including damage), but does not suffer the –2 Agility penalty for Normal gravity.","notes":"Science Fiction Companion page 11","additionalStats":{},"major":false},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.science-fiction-companion.1Fny3zPjVfjc8jn2"},"cf":{"id":"temp_5fatrubp5nm","path":"Science Fiction Companion","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"VgkQLekZhMczOF3i"}
{"name":"Night Terrors","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"Your spacer suffers from terrible and intense nightmares. He tosses and turns like a chanouk on bad feed and often has to sleep by himself to keep from waking everyone else up.</p><p>The repeated barrage on his psyche results in an overall weakened resolve. He suffers a −1 penalty to all Spirit rolls (but not linked skills).","notes":"Deadlands Lost Colony page 35","additionalStats":{},"major":true},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.deadlands-lost-colony.8ItO4sc2v1SmNm4V"},"cf":{"id":"temp_3ki8vx1qg59","path":"Deadlands: Lost Colony","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"Y66y1q75uY4lzzQL"}
{"name":"Forsaken","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"Banshee embraces most of the life forms that walk, crawls, or slithers upon it—but not all. The living planet just doesn’t take a liking to some folks.</p><p>Forsaken cannot benefit from anouk magic in any way. They may still be affected by damaging effects normally, however.</p><p>Any Guardian or anouk shaman who gets within a dozen yards or so and makes a Notice roll immediately recognizes the condition. If outed, the Forsaken has the Outsider (Minor) Hindrance with all other anouks in that particular area.</p><p>Forsaken can never become a Guardian or anouk shaman, and can never develop the Tannis Bond or Tannis Touch Edges.","notes":"Deadlands Lost Colony page 34","additionalStats":{},"major":true},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.deadlands-lost-colony.nKf0nr9VEkPPgSPf"},"cf":{"id":"temp_3ki8vx1qg59","path":"Deadlands: Lost Colony","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"dnyae48xywMqCevq"}
{"name":"Cursed","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"Some dark event cursed your colonist or anouk. It may have happened recently, long ago, or might have even something passed down through her family. Whatever the source, things just don’t seem to go her way.</p><p>For each player character with the Cursed Hindrance, the GM starts with one additional Benny!","notes":"Deadlands Lost Colony page 34","additionalStats":{},"major":true},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.deadlands-lost-colony.XaBPoptEtcoMC1Ib"},"cf":{"id":"temp_3ki8vx1qg59","path":"Deadlands: Lost Colony","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"jeDzuInmSWxPKHcv"}
{"name":"Tenderfoot","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"Every little ol’ cut and scrape makes your cowpoke cry for mama. As long as he has at least one Wound, he suffers an additional −1 penalty to all his actions (so a hero with 2 Wounds suffers a −3 penalty, for example). A whiner with this Hindrance can’t take the Don’t Get ’im Riled! Edge.","notes":"Deadlands Lost Colony page 35","additionalStats":{},"major":true},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.deadlands-lost-colony.4BWURg0Fb3VTWjA3"},"cf":{"id":"temp_3ki8vx1qg59","path":"Deadlands: Lost Colony","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"ky8GQmwKoDOG9tYY"}
{"name":"Cyber Resistant","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"Cyberware doesn’t take in this spacer’s body. She may never have cyberware installed. If it is for some reason, it doesn’t function. This Hindrance may only be taken if cyberware is relatively prominent in the campaign. Cyberware is described on page 29.","notes":"Science Fiction Companion page 11","additionalStats":{},"major":false},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.science-fiction-companion.9EZzxhAoDOlZwWHp"},"cf":{"id":"temp_5fatrubp5nm","path":"Science Fiction Companion","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"nANbsnbEt51Frjy0"}
{"name":"Ailin’","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"Your colonist or anouk has some sort of incurable disease or sickness. She might have picked up a weird bug on Banshee (or from the humans), inherited it, or maybe just came into contact with some strange and horrible creature. The Minor version of the Hindrance means you subtract 1 from any roll made to resist Fatigue from any source. Subtract 2 if it’s a Major Hindrance.</p><p>A Critical Failure on such a roll means things are getting worse. If your spacer has the Minor version, she gets worse and her Hindrance becomes Major. If she already has the Major version, the Reaper comes calling. It’s your choice when and how this happens. She might go out in a blaze of glory or surrounded by friends on a peaceful mountain top. The good news is you gain an immediate point of Conviction. When your character finally passes, the other player characters gain a point of Conviction, drawing strength from the brave passing of their stalwart companion.</p><p>Of course you can also buy off your Hindrance by spending an Advance (two for the Major version of the Hindrance). You should also work with the GM to figure out a narrative reason for the improvement—treatment at an advance facility, a miracle cure, a transfusion from a unique donor, or some other story-based explanation for the character’s miraculous improvement.","notes":"Deadlands Lost Colony page 34","additionalStats":{},"major":true},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.deadlands-lost-colony.0eBiEtRNZXb08eGk"},"cf":{"id":"temp_3ki8vx1qg59","path":"Deadlands: Lost Colony","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"pnorjY2t78YsNgPx"}
{"name":"Heavy Sleeper","type":"hindrance","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/hindrance.svg","data":{"description":"A thunderstorm from Hell itself doesn’t wake this Napping Nellie. If commotion gives the heroine a chance to wake, she makes her Notice roll at −4. She also suffers a −4 penalty to Vigor rolls made to stay awake.","notes":"Deadlands Lost Colony page 35","additionalStats":{},"major":false},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.deadlands-lost-colony.2ctNnxfu2d3Mgeh9"},"cf":{"id":"temp_3ki8vx1qg59","path":"Deadlands: Lost Colony","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"qmCo5Ky4OTqkTSHL"}
